Diana Joseph quoted in Barron's
      Microchip's Savvy Game Plan 
By JACQUELINE DOHERTY
Diana discussed a microcontroller company which the firm views as being undervalued, suggesting that if developed economies grow modestly in the next few years, and emerging markets grow by 4%, Microchip Technology ought to see 10% to 15% annual profit growth.
Barron's � October 8, 2011

Diana Joseph quoted in Barron's
      Dow Drops 6.4% in Worst Week Since Fall 2008
By JACQUELINE DOHERTY
In view of the market's selloff, there are a number of companies that have financial metrics at or near the low-end of their 10-year range, says Diana Joseph, chief investment officer at Barrington Strategic Wealth Management Group. PepsiCo (PEP), for example, has price-to-book, price-to-cash-flow and price-to-earnings ratios that are close to 10-year lows, Joseph notes. Yes, there are concerns that the company has lost market share to chief rival Coca-Cola (KO). But it has exposure to the emerging markets and its growing nutritional foods business makes the company particularly attractive, along with its 3.4% dividend yield.
Barron's � September 24, 2011

GM stock rolls back into the shop
Chicago Sun Times � March 27, 2011

Diana Joseph quoted in Barron's
        There's Safety in These Numbers
By DIMITRA DEFOTIS
Procter & Gamble had a tougher time in this span, as earnings grew only 4%. But the company's exposure to faster-growing foreign markets, which account for 58% of sales, and its valuation at 15.2 times this year's expected earnings, make the stock attractive. P&G could generate total returns of 8% to 10% in each of the next five years, says Diana Joseph, chief investment officer at Barrington Wealth Management Group in Chicago.
Barron's � March 19, 2011

Fear of defaults putting pressure on municipal bonds
Chicago Tribune � December 29, 2010

